\sectd\plain\pgwsxn12240\pghsxn15840\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\margtsxn1440\margbsxn1920\headery0\footery0\pgndec\titlepg{\headerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i\fs20 \chpgn }\par}{\headerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i\fs20 Cygwin/X Frequently Asked Questions}\par}{\footerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i\fs20 \chpgn }\par}{\headerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i\fs20 Cygwin/X Frequently Asked Questions}\par}{\footerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i\fs20 \chpgn }\par}\pard\sb373\li960\sl647\qc {\*\bkmkstart ID_cygwin_45_x_45_faq}{\*\bkmkend ID_cygwin_45_x_45_faq}\b\fs49\f1 Cygwin/X Frequently Asked Questions\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s2\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_qanda}{\*\bkmkend ID_qanda}\fs34 Questions and Answers\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_general}{\*\bkmkend ID_general}\fs20\f0 1. General Information\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_what_45_is_45_cygwin_45_x}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_what_45_is_45_cygwin_45_x}1.1. \b0 What is Cygwin/X?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260  Cygwin/X is a port of the X Window System to Cygwin. Cygwin provides a UNIX-like API on the Win32 platform. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_what_45_is_45_cygwin}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_what_45_is_45_cygwin}\b 1.2. \b0 What is Cygwin?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Cygwin tools are, in the words of the Cygwin homepage (http://cygwin.com/), \'93ports of the popular GNU development tools and utilities for Windows 95, 98, and NT. They function by using the Cygwin library which provides a UNIX-like API on top of the Win32 API.\'94 Cygwin provides the compiler (gcc), libraries, headers, and other utilities which build and support the operation of Cygwin/X.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_what_45_is_45_x_45_window_45_system}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_what_45_is_45_x_45_window_45_system}\b 1.3. \b0 What is the X Window System?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 [ScheiflerGettys92]\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 The X Window System, or X, is a network-transparent window system. With X, multiple applications can run simultaneously in windows, generating text and graphics in monochrome or color on a bitmap display. Network transparency means that application programs can run on machines scattered through the network.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_what_45_is_45_x_45_server}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_what_45_is_45_x_45_server}\b 1.4. \b0 What is an X Server?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 An X Server is a program that provides display and user input services to other programs. In comparison, a file server provides other programs with access to file storage devices. File servers are typically located in a remote location and you use the services of a file server from the machine that you are located at. In contrast, an X Server is typically running on the machine that you are located at; display and user input services may be requested by programs running on your machine, as well as by programs running on remote machines.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_what_45_is_45_x_45_client}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_what_45_is_45_x_45_client}\b 1.5. \b0 What is an X client?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 An X client is a program that utilizes the display and user input services provided by an X Server. X clients may run on the same or disparate machine as the X Server that is providing display and user input services.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_display_45_and_45_screen}{\*\bkmkend ID_display_45_and_45_screen}\b 1.6. \b0 What does :0.0 mean?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 The \i\fs18\f2 :0.0\i0\fs20\f0  part of the \i\fs18\f2 DISPLAY\i0\fs20\f0  variable denote the display and the screen of an X server.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 The display is the first number and equals to a running instance of an X server. If it is using TCP/IP for communication it listens on port 6000 + \i\fs18\f2 display-number\i0\fs20\f0  for connections. With local (UNIX domain sockets) it uses the socket \fs18\f2 /tmp/.X11-unix/X\i\fs16 display-number\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \i0\fs20\f0 The screen denotes different output devices of the X server. You could start \fs18\f2 XWin.exe\fs20\f0  with two \i\fs18\f2 -screen\i0\fs20\f0  options and would end up with two X11 windows. Each of them is a different screen. Other X servers open different screens for different monitors connected to the computer.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 Cygwin/X supports different formats of the \i\fs18\f2 DISPLAY\i0\fs20\f0  variable \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1640\sl260\fi-200 \tx1640 \fs16 \'95\tab \i\fs18\f2 :0.0\i0\fs20\f0  or \i\fs18\f2 unix:0.0\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1640\sl260 \i0\fs20\f0 This names a local X server and the communication uses the UNIX domain sockets.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1640\sl260\fi-200 \tx1640 \fs16 \'95\tab \i\fs18\f2 hostname:0.0\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1640\sl260 \i0\fs20\f0 This names a remote X server and the communication uses the TCP/IP network.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_why_45_port_45_to_45_windows}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_why_45_port_45_to_45_windows}\b\lang1024 1.7. \b0 Why port the X Window System to Microsoft Windows?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Porting X Window System to Microsoft Windows benefits many people and projects in many ways:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1640\sl260\fi-200 \tx1640 \fs16 \'95\tab \fs20 Prior to Cygwin/X only commercial, closed source X Servers were available for Microsoft Windows.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1640\sl260\fi-200 \tx1640 \fs16 \'95\tab \fs20 An X Server on Windows may be used to display the output of programs running on remote UNIX machines.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1640\sl260\fi-200 \tx1640 \fs16 \'95\tab \fs20 Cygwin/X, in conjunction with Cygwin, provides a complete compatibility layer for compiling and running UNIX applications on Microsoft Windows.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_newsgroup}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_newsgroup}\b 1.8. \b0 Is there a Cygwin/X newsgroup?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 No, Cygwin/X does not have a newsgroup; however, we do have a mailing list. See {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_mailing_45_list}{\fldrslt Q: 1.9.}}\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_mailing_45_list}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_mailing_45_list}\b 1.9. \b0 Is there a Cygwin/X mailing list?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Yes, Cygwin/X has a mailing list, namely, cygwin-xfree@cygwin.com. Visit the Cygwin Mailing Lists (http://cygwin.com/lists.html) page to subscribe to cygwin-xfree@cygwin.com as well as to read and search an online archive of the mailing list traffic.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1840\sl234 \b\fs18\f1 Tip: \b0 Post your X-related inquires to cygwin-xfree@cygwin.com only; do not post nor cross post your inquires to the cygwin@cygwin.com mailing list. Cygwin's mailing list is only for Cygwin related inquires that are not handled by another more-specific list.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li960\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_installation}{\*\bkmkend ID_installation}\b\fs20\f0 2. Installation\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_windows_45_versions_45_supported}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_windows_45_versions_45_supported}2.1. \b0 What versions of Windows does Cygwin/X run on?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Cygwin/X aims to support all versions of Windows supported by Cygwin. However, Cygwin/X has not been tested on older versions of Windows and is believed to be broken. Problem reports are welcomed.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 Cygwin/X requires Cygwin to compile and run. Cygwin is not, as of 2003-12-29, available on Microsoft Windows CE, therefore Cygwin/X is not currently available on Microsoft Windows CE.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_how_45_to_45_install}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_how_45_to_45_install}\b\lang1024 2.2. \b0 How is Cygwin/X installed?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 The Cygwin/X User's Guide (http://x.cygwin.com/docs/ug/cygwin-x-ug.html) thoroughly documents the installation process. Installation is performed through Cygwin's \b setup.exe\b0  program.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li960\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_modular}{\*\bkmkend ID_modular}\b 3. Upgrade\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_x_45_is_45_broke}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_x_45_is_45_broke}3.1. \b0 What happened to my X server? Where did \fs18\f2 /usr/X11R6/\fs20\f0  go? \keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 The upgrade from X.Org R6.8 to modular X.Org R7.4 makes a lot of changes. Please read the announce email (http://cygwin.com/ml/cygwin-xfree-announce/2008-11/msg00000.html) and pay attention to the upgrade instructions \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_i_45_cant_45_type_45_anything}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_i_45_cant_45_type_45_anything}\b 3.2. \b0 I upgraded my X server and now I can't type anything into any X application\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260  Launch the X server via the shortcut under "Cygwin-X" on the start menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 Technical details: The \b startxwin.bat\b0  script used to set several enviroment variables used by the X server to specify the location of files it needs to access. Specifically this batch file would set \i\fs18\f2 XKEYSYMDB\i0\fs20\f0  to \fs18\f2 /usr/X11R6/lib/X11/XKeysymDB\fs20\f0 . This file is now at \fs18\f2 /usr/share/X11/XKeysymDB\fs20\f0 , and without it the keyboard won't work.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 If you are (perhaps unintentionally) using a copy of the old \b startxwin.bat\b0  (perhaps under another name) to start the X server, remove the environment variables \i\fs18\f2 XAPPLRESDIR\i0\fs20\f0 , \i\fs18\f2 XCMSDB\i0\fs20\f0 , \i\fs18\f2 XNLSPATH\i0\fs20\f0  and \i\fs18\f2 XKEYSYMDB\i0\fs20\f0  from it, or (preferrably) use the updated \b startxwin.bat\b0 .\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 If \b echo $XKEYSYMDB\b0  outputs something, you have something else setting \i\fs18\f2 XKEYSYMDB\i0\fs20\f0  in your environment. Find it and remove it.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 These variables were always being set to the defaults, so they can simply be removed. See {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_microsoft_45_services_45_for_45_unix}{\fldrslt Q: 8.8.}} for the reason why you might need to set them.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_whereis_45_startxwin_45_bat}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_whereis_45_startxwin_45_bat}\b\lang1024 3.3. \b0 I can't find \b startxwin.bat\b0  to start the X server\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260  X.Org now uses the prefix \fs18\f2 /usr\fs20\f0  not \fs18\f2 /usr/X11R6\fs20\f0 . So \b startxwin.bat\b0  has moved from \fs18\f2 /usr/X11R6/bin/startxwin.bat\fs20\f0  to \fs18\f2 /usr/bin/startxwin.bat\fs20\f0 . \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 A "XWin Server" shortcut to this batch file is created on the Start menu, under "Cygwin-X"\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \b startxwin.bat\b0  and the Start menu link to it are now installed by the \fs18\f2 xinit\fs20\f0  package.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_cant_45_read_45_lock_45_file}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_cant_45_read_45_lock_45_file}\b\lang1024 3.4. \b0 Fatal server error: Can't read lock file /tmp/.X0-lock\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 The cause of this problem is not well understood at present. Possible causes:\hyphpar0\par\pard\li1800\sl260\fi-360 \tqr\tx1750\tx1800\tab 1.\tab \fs18\f2 /tmp\fs20\f0  resides on a FAT filesystem\hyphpar0\par\pard\li1800\sl260\fi-360 \tqr\tx1750\tx1800\tab 2.\tab Bad permissions on \fs18\f2 /tmp\hyphpar0\par\pard\li1800\sl260\fi-360 \tqr\tx1750\tx1800\tab \fs20\f0 3.\tab Not having administrator rights\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 Possible workarounds:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1800\sl260\fi-360 \tqr\tx1750\tx1800\tab \lang1024 1.\tab Try starting the server with \i\fs18\f2 -nolock\i0\fs20\f0  (e.g. if you use \fs18\f2 startxwin.bat\fs20\f0  or \fs18\f2 startxwin.sh\fs20\f0  to start the server, add \i\fs18\f2 -nolock\i0\fs20\f0  to the \b XWin\b0  line in that script; if you use \b xinit\b0  or \b startx\b0 , run it as \b xinit -- -nolock\b0  or \b startx -- -nolock\b0 )\hyphpar0\par\pard\li1800\sl260\fi-360 \tqr\tx1750\tx1800\tab 2.\tab Try \b rm -rf /tmp; mkdir /tmp ; chmod 1777 /tmp\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \b0\lang1033 Technical details: The X server attempts to create a lock file in \fs18\f2 /tmp\fs20\f0  by creating the file under a temporary name, then renaming it to the proper name (by hard linking it under the correct name, then unlinking it from the temporary name). If this rename fails it attempts to read the existing lock file to determine the pid of an already running server. The failure case appears to be that lock file was created successfully, but the rename failed, despite the fact that no old lock file exists, which we then fail to read (hence the error message).\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_where_45_are_45_my_45_fonts}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_where_45_are_45_my_45_fonts}\b\lang1024 3.5. \b0 My favourite font has gone! The font Emacs uses is just boxes\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260  Only minimal fonts will be installed after the upgrade. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 Font packages are now named \fs18\f2 font-<author/class>-<fonttype>\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \fs20\f0 Some packages dependencies have not yet been updated for the fonts they require, so you may need to manually install the needed fonts. For example, to provide the font emacs wants to use by default you will probably want to install \fs18\f2 font-adobe-dpi75\fs20\f0  (or \fs18\f2 font-adobe-dpi100\fs20\f0  if you like large fonts). This package provides the \i\fs18\f2 courier\i0\fs20\f0 , \i\fs18\f2 helvetica\i0\fs20\f0 , \i\fs18\f2 new century schoolbook\i0\fs20\f0  and \i\fs18\f2 times\i0\fs20\f0  font families.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 The \i\fs18\f2 lucida\i0\fs20\f0  font family is provided by the package \fs18\f2 font-bh-dpi75\fs20\f0  (or \fs18\f2 font-bh-dpi100\fs20\f0 ). The monospaced version, \i\fs18\f2 lucida typewriter\i0\fs20\f0  is provided by the package \fs18\f2 font-bh-lucidatypewriter-dpi75\fs20\f0  (or \fs18\f2 font-bh-lucidatypewriter-dpi100\fs20\f0 ).\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 Note that after installing fonts you will need to restart the X server or run \b xset fp default; xset fp rehash\b0  to make the new fonts available\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_where_45_is_45_xxyzy}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_where_45_is_45_xxyzy}\b\lang1024 3.6. \b0 Where has \b xhost\b0 /\b xlsfonts\b0 /etc. gone?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Previously all the X utility programs were contained in a single package, \fs18\f2 xorg-x11-bin\fs20\f0 , which needed to be updated when any of the programs it contained was updated. In modular X each of these programs can be found in a separate package, usually named \b xhost\b0 /\b xlsfont\b0 /etc.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_how_45_do_45_i_45_get_45_rid_45_of_45_xterm_45_menu}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_how_45_do_45_i_45_get_45_rid_45_of_45_xterm_45_menu}\b 3.7. \b0 How do I get rid of that menu at the top of my xterm?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Run it as \b xterm +tb\b0 , or add \i\fs18\f2 XTerm*toolBar: false\i0\fs20\f0  to \fs18\f2 ~/.Xdefaults\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_ssh_45_y}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_ssh_45_y}\b\fs20\f0 3.8. \b0 ssh -X now says "Warning: untrusted X11 forwarding setup failed: xauth key data not generated"\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 See {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_ssh_45_no_45_x11forwarding}{\fldrslt Q: 6.1.}}. See point 3 in this mail (http://cygwin.com/ml/cygwin-xfree/2008-11/msg00154.html). Use ssh -Y.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 Technical details: ssh tried to run \b xauth generate\b0  to create a untrusted cookie for the session, which failed because the server isn't compiled with the XCSECURITY extension built-in.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_nedit_45_wont_45_start}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_nedit_45_wont_45_start}\b\lang1024 3.9. \b0 \b nedit\b0  fails to start with an error message \keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\f2 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
