\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li960\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_configuration}{\*\bkmkend ID_configuration}\b\fs20\lang1024\f0 4. Configuration\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_why_45_no_45_xf86config}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_why_45_no_45_xf86config}4.1. \b0 Is there an xorg.conf or XF86Config file?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 No. But most of the options which were configurable in the configfile are now available as command line options. For more information on configuring other keyboard layouts see {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_non_45_U_46_S_46__45_keyboard_45_layout}{\fldrslt Q: 5.1.1.}}\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_command_45_line_45_args}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_command_45_line_45_args}\b 4.2. \b0 What are the command line arguments for \fs18\f2 XWin.exe\fs20\f0 ?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 The Cygwin/X User's Guide (http://x.cygwin.com/docs/ug/cygwin-x-ug.html) documents the command line arguments for XWin.exe.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_display_45_depth_45_ignored}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_display_45_depth_45_ignored}\b 4.3. \b0 Why does \fs18\f2 XWin.exe\fs20\f0  ignore the display depth that I pass on the command line?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 When running in windowed mode or GDI-based fullscreen mode, \fs18\f2 XWin.exe\fs20\f0  must run the X Server at whatever display depth Windows is currently using; in these cases the display depth passed on the command line is ignored. \fs18\f2 XWin.exe\fs20\f0  only uses the display depth parameter when running in a DirectDraw-based fullscreen mode, as DirectDraw allows applications to change the display resolution and depth when running in fullscreen mode.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_three_45_button_45_emulation}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_three_45_button_45_emulation}\b 4.4. \b0 I have a two button mouse, can I emulate a three button mouse?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Yes. Pass the \i\fs18\f2 -emulate3buttons \fs16 timeout_in_milliseconds\i0\fs20\f0  parameter to \fs18\f2 XWin.exe\fs20\f0 , where \i\fs18\f2 timeout_in_milliseconds\i0\fs20\f0  is the, optional, maximum number of milliseconds between a button release and opposite button press that will trigger an emulated third button press.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_window_45_auto_45_focus}{\*\bkmkend ID_window_45_auto_45_focus}\b 4.5. \b0 Is there a Focus-Follows-Mouse feature (Auto-Focus)?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 This is a setting of the windowmanager used. The default windowmanager twm has no such feature. But with fvwm2 this can be achieved with the this configuration entry: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\f2 Focus FocusFollowsMouse\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \fs20\f0 Other windowmanagers (eg. windowmaker) have similar features too.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 If you are using the \i\fs18\f2 -multiwindow\i0\fs20\f0  mode you can not set this behaviour in the windowmanager but you can use the TweakUI tool to enable this feature for all windows, not limited to Cygwin/X windows.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_disable_45_terminate_45_server}{\*\bkmkend ID_disable_45_terminate_45_server}\b\lang1024 4.6. \b0 The option -nounixkill has no effect. How can i prevent the server shutdown an Ctrl-Alt-BackSpace?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 There is a keybinding to Ctrl-Alt-BackSpace which is named TerminateServer. Remove this binding and Ctrl-Alt-BackSpace will have no effect. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\f2 xmodmap -e "keycode 22 = BackSpace"\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \fs20\f0 \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_multihead}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_multihead}\b 4.7. \b0 I have a multihead system. Do I need special options to make it work? I have a multihead system. Why are my X-application windows white?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 You should start \fs18\f2 XWin.exe\fs20\f0  with the \i\fs18\f2 -multiplemonitors\i0\fs20\f0  options\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_firewall}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_firewall}\b 4.8. \b0 I have a firewall. Is there anything I have to take care of? \keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 \fs18\f2 XWin.exe\fs20\f0  uses port 6000/TCP by default. You will have to allow incoming and outgoing traffic on this port even if you are only using local clients. \fs18\f2 XWin.exe\fs20\f0  has a builtin access control so you won't have to worry about opening the port. If you are still concerned about security, you may limit the allowed hosts to 127.0.0.1 (localhost) and the local IP addresses.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 If you use a different \i\fs18\f2 DISPLAY\i0\fs20\f0  variable check section {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_display_45_and_45_screen}{\fldrslt Q: 1.6.}} for details about which ports are used. For additional information about firewalls and XDMCP connections check {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_mandrake_45_8_46_1_45_xdmcp}{\fldrslt Q: 7.4.}}.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li960\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_i18n}{\*\bkmkend ID_i18n}\b\lang1024 5. Internationalization\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_i18n_45_keyboard}{\*\bkmkend ID_i18n_45_keyboard}5.1. Keyboard support\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_non_45_U_46_S_46__45_keyboard_45_layout}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_non_45_U_46_S_46__45_keyboard_45_layout}5.1.1. \b0 How do I use a non-U.S. keyboard layout?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1920\sl260 Some keyboard layouts are autodetected from the Windows keyboard settings. For these layouts no special change is needed. For all other layouts there is the possibility to configure the layout via commandline options.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1920\sl260 \lang1033 The mainoption for changing the layout is \i\fs18\f2 -xkblayout \fs16 countrycode\i0\fs20\f0  where \i\fs18\f2 countrycode\i0\fs20\f0  is in most cases the 2 character code which also represents the country in internet adresses (e.g. Australia = au, Deutschland = de, France = fr, Japan = jp)\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1920\sl260 Other options for tweaking the XKB layout are \i\fs18\f2 -xkbmodel\i0\fs20\f0 ,\i\fs18\f2 -xkbvariant\i0\fs20\f0 , \i\fs18\f2 -xkboptions\i0\fs20\f0  and \i\fs18\f2 -xkbrules\i0\fs20\f0 . These are the counterparts for the similar named options known from the xorg.conf file.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1920\sl260 If the loading fails, check {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_xkb_45_not_45_working}{\fldrslt Q: 5.1.6.}}\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_submit_45_layout}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_submit_45_layout}\b\lang1024 5.1.2. \b0 I there a way to add a layout to the list of autodetected?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1920\sl260 If your keyboard layout is not automatically detected you can send the required information for including it into Cygwin/X to cygwin-xfree@cygwin.com. Please include the following information in your mail:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li2120\sl260\fi-200 \tx2120 \fs16 \'95\tab \fs20 The windows keyboard layout code and the layout name\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li2120\sl260 \lang1033 You will find it in \fs18\f2 /var/log/XWin.0.log\fs20\f0  in lines similar to these: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li2120\sl234 \fs18\f2 (--) winConfigKeyboard - Layout: "00001809" (00001809)\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
(EE) Keyboardlayout "Irish" (00001809) is unknown\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li2120\sl260\fi-200 \tx2120 \fs16\lang1024\f0 \'95\tab \fs20 The XKB layout code for this layout if you know it. Please experiment with \b setxkbmap\b0  or \i\fs18\f2 -xkblayout\i0\fs20\f0  (as described in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_non_45_U_46_S_46__45_keyboard_45_layout}{\fldrslt Q: 5.1.1.}}) to find a XKB layout code which works for you, otherwise the maintainers will have to guess it.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li2120\sl260\fi-200 \tx2120 \fs16 \'95\tab \fs20 A description how the layout looks like. This makes it easy to identify the matching XKB layout code. Many layouts are available from the Microsoft Global Dev (http://www.microsoft.com/globaldev/reference/keyboards.mspx) website. Just add a link to your layout.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_modmap_45_obtaining}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_modmap_45_obtaining}\b 5.1.3. \b0 Where can I find an xmodmap for my non-U.S. keyboard layout?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1920\sl260 This question should be obsolete The package \fs18\f2 xkeyboard-config\fs20\f0  should contain just about any needed layout\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 Or, you can use \b xkeycaps\b0  to automatically generate a modmap for one of over 208 different layouts. See the xkeycaps home page (http://www.jwz.org/xkeycaps/) to download and for more information.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_how_45_modmap_45_and_45_xdmcp}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_how_45_modmap_45_and_45_xdmcp}\b 5.1.4. \b0 How do I get my non-U.S. keyboard modmap to be installed when using xdmcp?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1920\sl260 See {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_non_45_U_46_S_46__45_keyboard_45_layout}{\fldrslt Q: 5.1.1.}}\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_aix_45_xkb}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_aix_45_xkb}\b 5.1.5. \b0 Logging into AIX via XDMCP causes the keyboard to function as if \b AltGr\b0  is permanently pressed.\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1920\sl260 [Pavel Rybnicek] The X Keyboard Extension doesn't work with AIX. The X Keyboard Extension is enabled by default, so you must disable it with the \i\fs18\f2 -kb\i0\fs20\f0  parameter. An example command line follows.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1920\sl260 \b\fs18\lang1033\f2 XWin.exe -kb -query \i\fs16 aix_hostname_or_ip_address\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_xkb_45_not_45_working}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_xkb_45_not_45_working}\i0\fs20\lang1024\f0 5.1.6. \b0 Loading XKB keymaps fails\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1920\sl260 First check if you are able to change the server to another layout via XKB. The german layout will be good for testing: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl234 \fs18\f2 setxkbmap de -model pc105\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 \fs20\f0  This worked if pressing "Shift" and "8" produces "(" instead of "*". If it worked then you can skip the next paragraph.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1920\sl260 \lang1033 There is currently a problem with the /tmp directory mounted in textmode. You can change the setting to binmode with: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl234 \fs18\f2 mount -b "$(cygpath -m /tmp)" /tmp\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 \fs20\f0  If this fails with an errormessage stating unsufficient rights, try \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl234 \fs18\f2 mount -b -u "$(cygpath -m /tmp)" /tmp\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 \fs20\f0 Not all keyboard layouts are tested very well and some contain errors or do not work at all. To test if the compiling of your layout works start \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl234 \fs18\f2 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
setxkbmap \i\fs16 de\i0\fs18  -print | xkbcomp -w3 -xkm - localhost:0.0\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 \fs20\f0  (replace the "de" with your layout code). This may produce warnings, but must not produce errors. If there are errors then please report them to the mailinglist.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1920\sl260 XXX: This answer needs updating\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_alt_45_gr_45_win_45_xp_45_powertoys}{\*\bkmkend ID_alt_45_gr_45_win_45_xp_45_powertoys}\b\lang1024 5.1.7. \b0 I have Windows XP with Powertoys installed and AltGr does not work. What can I do?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1920\sl260 This problem is solved in recent Cygwin/X releases. Use cygwin setup to upgrade the xorg-server package. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_alt_45_gr_45_with_45_old_45_x}{\*\bkmkend ID_alt_45_gr_45_with_45_old_45_x}\b 5.1.8. \b0 AltGr does not work properly when connecting to other unices or to old XFree86.\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1920\sl260 The older X11 releases on the various commercial unices define the AltGr key as ModeSwitch, MetaR, AltR or similar. Cygwin/X expects it to be ISO_Level3_Switch. For reasons unknown to us this is reset when logging into the remote host. As far as we don't have access to such a machine we are unable to track this down and find a reason.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1920\sl260 \lang1033 Sometimes it does help to run \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl234 \fs18\f2 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
DISPLAY=:0.0 setxkbmap \i\fs16 languagecode\i0\fs18 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 \fs20\f0  from a cygwin shell. For more information see {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_non_45_U_46_S_46__45_keyboard_45_layout}{\fldrslt Q: 5.1.1.}}.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_i18n_45_display}{\*\bkmkend ID_i18n_45_display}\b\lang1024 5.2. Display problems\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_bash_45_extended_45_chars}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_bash_45_extended_45_chars}5.2.1. \b0 How do I get \b bash\b0  to display accents and/or umlauts?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1920\sl260 (Heinz Peter Hippenstiel) Add the following lines to \fs18\f2 .inputrc\fs20\f0  in your Cygwin home directory (e.g. \fs18\f2 /home/harold/\fs20\f0 ): \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl234 \fs18\f2 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
set meta-flag on\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
set output-meta on # to show 8-bit characters\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
