\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1920\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_bash_45_8bit}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_bash_45_8bit}\b\fs20\f0 5.2.2. \b0 How do I put \b bash\b0  into \'938 bit\'94 mode?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1920\sl260 See {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_bash_45_extended_45_chars}{\fldrslt Q: 5.2.1.}}\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li960\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_remote}{\*\bkmkend ID_remote}\b 6. Remote connections\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_ssh_45_no_45_x11forwarding}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_ssh_45_no_45_x11forwarding}6.1. \b0 X11Forwarding does not work with OpenSSH under Cygwin\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 A1:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 OpenSSH 3.8 enables untrusted X11 forwarding by default when connecting to an ssh server that supports untrusted {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_gloss_45_x11forwarding}{\fldrslt \i X11Forwarding}}. Most ssh servers for GNU/Linux are versions of OpenSSH that do support untrusted X11Forwarding, so using OpenSSH 3.8 from Cygwin will result in a connection that uses untrusted X11Forwarding by default. You will quickly notice that this is the case if most of your X applications are now killed when you try to copy and paste or if \b xdpyinfo\b0  returns only a fraction of the supported extensions that it does if run locally.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 It is easiest to just override untrusted X11Forwarding by passing \i\fs18\f2 -Y\i0\fs20\f0  to \b ssh\b0  in place of \i\fs18\f2 -X\i0\fs20\f0 . The \i\fs18\f2 -Y\i0\fs20\f0  does the same thing as \i\fs18\f2 -X\i0\fs20\f0 , but it enables trusted X11Forwarding for the current connection.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \lang1024 A2:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 Before establishing the ssh connection the xserver must be started and the environment variable \i\fs18\f2 DISPLAY\i0\fs20\f0  must be set for ssh. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\f2 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
$ DISPLAY=\i\fs16 localhost:0.0\i0\fs18 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
$ export DISPLAY\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
$ ssh -Y \i\fs16 remotehost\i0\fs18 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \fs20\f0  or \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\f2 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
$ DISPLAY=\i\fs16 localhost:0.0\i0\fs18  ssh -Y \i\fs16 remotehost\i0\fs18 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \fs20\f0 The parameter \i\fs18\f2 -Y\i0\fs20\f0  enables trusted X11Forwarding. This is available since OpenSSH 3.8. If you have an older version of ssh you will have to use \i\fs18\f2 -X\i0\fs20\f0 .\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \lang1024 A3:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 Make sure you're not starting ssh with the parameter \i\fs18\f2 -x\i0\fs20\f0  (lowercase). This disables X11Forwarding.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \lang1024 A4:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 Check that X11Forwarding is not disabled in the openssh client configuration.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 The configfiles are by default \fs18\f2 ~/.ssh/config\fs20\f0  and \fs18\f2 /etc/ssh_config\fs20\f0 . The file in the home directory overrides settings in the global one.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 The configfile is split into various sections starting with \'93Host \i\fs18\f2 wildcard\i0\fs20\f0 \'94. The section applies to all hosts where \i\fs18\f2 wildcard\i0\fs20\f0  matches the hostname.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 If this section contains an entry \'93ForwardX11 no\'94 then X11Forwarding is disabled. To enable it change the entry to:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\lang1024\f2 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
ForwardX11 yes\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \fs20\lang1033\f0 Starting with OpenSSH 3.8 you will need the switch \'93ForwardX11Trusted yes\'94 in the client configuration to allow remote clients full access to the xserver. Without it some clients will fail with a similar error:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\lang1024\f2  X Error of failed request: BadAtom (invalid Atom parameter)\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
  Major opcode of failed request: 18 (X_ChangeProperty)\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
  Atom id in failed request: 0x114\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
  Serial number of failed request: 370\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
  Current serial number in output stream: 372\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \fs20\lang1033\f0 The commandline switch \i\fs18\f2 -Y\i0\fs20\f0  does the same.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \lang1024 A5:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 Check that X11Forwarding is not disabled in the ssh server configuration.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 The configfile is by default \fs18\f2 /etc/ssh/sshd_config\fs20\f0 . If there is an entry \'93X11Forwarding no\'94 then X11Forwarding is disabled.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 If you have write access to the config file then change it to \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\f2 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
X11Forwarding yes\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \fs20\f0  Otherwise ask your you admin to change this for you.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \lang1024 A6:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 [Frederick W. Wheeler] If the \i remote\i0  machine is a Windows machine using Cygwin OpenSSH server, make sure the Cygwin \b xauth\b0  package is installed on the \i remote\i0  machine. The OpenSSH server needs to be able to run \b xauth\b0  to do X11 Forwarding.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_bad_45_atom}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_bad_45_atom}\b\lang1024 6.2. \b0 Why do remote programs crash with X Error of failed request: BadAtom? \keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Starting with OpenSSH 3.8 you will need to set \'93ForwardX11Trusted yes\'94 in the client configuration to allow remote clients full access to the xserver. Without it some clients will fail with a similar error:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\f2  X Error of failed request: BadAtom (invalid Atom parameter)\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
  Major opcode of failed request: 18 (X_ChangeProperty)\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
  Atom id in failed request: 0x114\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
