\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_solaris_45_fonts}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_solaris_45_fonts}\b\fs20\lang1024\f0 7.6. \b0 I get no login screen for Solaris\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 See also {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_remote_45_solaris}{\fldrslt Q: 7.7.}} and {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_cde_45_via_45_xdmcp_45_hangs}{\fldrslt Q: 7.8.}}\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 [David Dawson] For whatever reason, certain versions of Solaris need fonts that are not provided by Cygwin/X; the result is that you may see the Solaris background tile and the hourglass cursor, but the XDM login prompt will never appear. The simplest solution is to point Cygwin/X at the font server that is usually running on the Solaris machine. You'll need a command line similar to the following to start your {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_gloss_45_xdmcp}{\fldrslt \i XDMCP}} session and to connect to the Solaris font server:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \b\fs18\lang1033\f2 XWin.exe -query \i\fs16 solaris_hostname_or_ip_address\i0\fs18  -fp tcp/\i\fs16 solaris_hostname_or_ip_address\i0\fs18 :7100\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1840\sl234 \lang1024\f1 Note: \b0 The \i\fs16\f2 -fp\i0\fs18\f1  parameter is a general X Server parameter, it is not specific to Cygwin/X; therefore, the \i\fs16\f2 -fp\i0\fs18\f1  is documented in the X Server manual page (http://freedesktop.org/~xorg/X11R6.7.0/doc/Xserver.1.html). For additional information about fonts, see Fonts in X11R6.7 (http://freedesktop.org/~xorg/X11R6.7.0/doc/fonts.html).\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \fs20\lang1033\f0 The standard port number for a font server is \fs18\f2 7100\fs20\f0 , however, you may need to ask your system administrator what the font server port number is if you cannot connect to a font server on port \fs18\f2 7100\fs20\f0 . It is also possible that your Solaris machine is not running a font server, in which case you will need to consult your Solaris documentation for instructions on how to run a font server.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_remote_45_solaris}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_remote_45_solaris}\b\lang1024 7.7. \b0 XDMCP freezes with remote Solaris machine!\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 See also {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_solaris_45_fonts}{\fldrslt Q: 7.6.}} and {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_cde_45_via_45_xdmcp_45_hangs}{\fldrslt Q: 7.8.}}\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 Solaris appears to not support certain display bit depths, such as 24 bits per pixel. Change your Windows display bit depth to 8, 16, or 32 and try logging in again. File a complaint with Sun if this issue is important to you, or change your Solaris machines to use XFree86 instead of the Solaris X Window System.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_cde_45_via_45_xdmcp_45_hangs}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_cde_45_via_45_xdmcp_45_hangs}\b 7.8. \b0 Login to CDE on Solaris via XDMCP hangs Cygwin/X.\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 See also {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_solaris_45_fonts}{\fldrslt Q: 7.6.}} and {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_remote_45_solaris}{\fldrslt Q: 7.7.}}\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 Install the recommended set of patches (http://www.sun.com/bigadmin/patches/indexRec.html) for your version of Solaris.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_xdmcp_45_info}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_xdmcp_45_info}\b 7.9. \b0 Where can I find more information about XDMCP.\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 See the Linux XDMCP HOWTO (http://en.tldp.org/HOWTO/XDMCP-HOWTO/) for more information about XDMCP.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li960\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_troubleshooting}{\*\bkmkend ID_troubleshooting}\b 8. Troubleshooting\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_fatal_45_error}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_fatal_45_error}8.1. \b0 Cygwin/X failed with "Fatal Error". What does this mean?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 The Fatal Error is a general error message. More specific information what caused this is available in \fs18\f2 /var/log/XWin.0.log\fs20\f0 . Please check the common error messages in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_errors}{\fldrslt the Section called \i Error and Warning Messages}}. If your error is not mentioned proceed with {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_error_45_message_45_not_45_listed}{\fldrslt Q: 8.4.}}\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_log_45_file_45_location}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_log_45_file_45_location}\b 8.2. \b0 Is there a log file that I can look at for diagnostic information and error messages?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Yes. The Cygwin/X log file is located at \fs18\f2 /var/log/XWin.0.log\fs20\f0 . You will find solutions to the most common error messages in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_errors}{\fldrslt the Section called \i Error and Warning Messages}}.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_error_45_message_45_interpretation}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_error_45_message_45_interpretation}\b 8.3. \b0 I have a specific error message, what does it mean?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 See the Error and Warning Messages section for help with specific error messages. Return to this section if you do not find a specific answer for the error message that you have.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_error_45_message_45_not_45_listed}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_error_45_message_45_not_45_listed}\b 8.4. \b0 I have a specific error message that is not addressed in the Error and Warning Messages section.\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Search the Cygwin/X mailing list archives (http://cygwin.com/ml/cygwin-xfree/) to see if the error message has already been reported and/or addressed. Report the error message to the Cygwin/X mailing list (cygwin-xfree@cygwin.com), how the error message was caused, and the behavior of the X Server after the error message was generated (exit, freeze, etc.), only if the error message has not been reported, if the circumstances that produced the error message are significantly different from other reports, or if you have additional information regarding the error message to contribute. Please include \fs18\f2 /var/log/XWin.0.log\fs20\f0  in your mail. This may help us identify the cause of your problem quicker.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_but_45_report_45_ignored}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_but_45_report_45_ignored}\b 8.5. \b0 My bug report the Cygwin/X mailing list was ignored. What do I do now?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Some bug reports are deliberately ignored by project members if the bug in question was recently dealt with; did you search the mailing list archives (project-url-ml-search;) for a solution to your problem before submitting your bug report? Some bug reports are ignored if they do not contain sufficient information to understand the situation that produces the bug; did your bug report have enough information? Some bug reports are missed or forgotten, thus some valid bug reports do not receive a reply; simply resubmit such bug reports that have not received a response within 7 days of submission.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_freeze_45_at_45_startup}{\*\bkmkend ID_freeze_45_at_45_startup}\b 8.6. \b0 Why does Cygwin/X freeze right after startup?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Zone Alarm 5 is known to break Cygwin/X. As a result you'll see this line (or a similar) as last output in \fs18\f2 /var/log/XWin.0.log\fs20\f0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\f2 Rules = "xorg" Model = "pc101" Layout = "us" Variant = "(null)" Options = "(null)"\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \fs20\f0 Disabling Zone Alarm will not solve this problem. You can only uninstall Zone Alarm 5 and switch to an earlier version (4.5 is known to work) or use a different personal firewall. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 Another reason is \fs18\f2 /tmp\fs20\f0  mounted in textmode. This does only happen with the \i\fs18\f2 -multiwindow\i0\fs20\f0  and \i\fs18\f2 -clipboard\i0\fs20\f0  switches because of the extra threads within Cygwin/X. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 You can remount \fs18\f2 /tmp\fs20\f0  to binmode with these commands: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\f2 mount -b "$(cygpath -m /tmp)" /tmp\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \fs20\f0  If this fails with an errormessage stating unsufficient rights, try \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\f2 mount -b -u "$(cygpath -m /tmp)" /tmp\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_poor_45_performance}{\*\bkmkend ID_poor_45_performance}\b\fs20\lang1024\f0 8.7. \b0 Cygwin/X has very poor performance. What's the reason?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Most likely you have installed some kind of personal firewall, VPN software or any other software that modifies the TCP/IP stack of Windows. Especially Webwasher and some other filtering software are known to slow down the network traffic.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 Some online virus scanners like Symantec Antivirus do slowdown Cygwin/X a lot. They scan every file access and network traffic which causes serious processing overhead beyond that from the X11 protocol and the unix emulation layer.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 So far there is no know solution but to disable the virus scanner completely.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \lang1024 [Dr. Edward Wornar] Certain programs that are installed by various drivers and software packages can consume an incredible amount of system resources and processing time. One known example of such a program is \fs18\f2 ATI2evxx.exe\fs20\f0 , a utility installed with some ATI Technologies graphics card drivers. Answers That Work (http://www.answersthatwork.com/) has information on \fs18\f2 ATI2evxx.exe\fs20\f0  on their Task List Programs - A (http://www.answersthatwork.com/Tasklist_pages/tasklist_a.htm) page. You may want to try disabling, one-by-one, \fs18\f2 ATI2evxx.exe\fs20\f0  and other such programs until you find the program that is causing the slowdown.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_microsoft_45_services_45_for_45_unix}{\*\bkmkend ID_microsoft_45_services_45_for_45_unix}\b 8.8. \b0 I have Microsoft Services for Unix installed and can't type anything. Help me!!!\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Microsoft Services for Unix set some environment variables which points Cygwin/X to outdated or not existing files. These variables are \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\f2 XAPPLRESDIR\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
XCMSDB\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
XKEYSYMDB\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
XNLSPATH\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \fs20\f0 To have Cygwin/X work correctly you have to unset at least \i\fs18\f2 XKEYSYMDB\i0\fs20\f0 . \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 Reported by Juan Medina, Pavel Rozenboim\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_tasklist_45_programs_45_slow}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_tasklist_45_programs_45_slow}\b\lang1024 8.9. \b0 Cygwin/X is extremely slow, especially when using XDMCP to connect to remote machines.\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 see {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_poor_45_performance}{\fldrslt Q: 8.7.}}.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_trackpoint}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_trackpoint}\b 8.10. \b0 IBM ThinkPad's with a TrackPoint mouse doesn't allow simulated mouse wheel scrolling.\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 [Gerald S. Williams] The TrackPoint driver tries to send scroll up/down messages to the default scrollbar in a window. Cygwin/X does not use Windows scrollbars for X Client windows, so we must configure the TrackPoint driver to send standard WM_MOUSEWHEEL messages to the Cygwin/X window. This can be done by editing the TrackPoint configuration file that can be found either in \fs18\f2 %SYSTEM_ROOT%\\System32\\tp4table.dat\fs20\f0  or \fs18\f2 %SYSTEM_ROOT%\\System32\\tp4scrol.dat\fs20\f0 . Add the following to the \'93Pass 0 rules\'94section: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\f2 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
; X Windows\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
*,*,XWin.exe,*,*,Cygwin/X,WheelStd,0,9\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \fs20\f0 \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_no_45_rootwindow_45_with_45_run}{\*\bkmkend ID_no_45_rootwindow_45_with_45_run}\b 8.11. \b0 Why is the root window not shown in normal mode?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 This is a small problem with \fs18\f2 run.exe\fs20\f0 . If you start \fs18\f2 XWin.exe\fs20\f0  with \i\fs18\f2 -nodecoration\i0\fs20\f0 , \i\fs18\f2 -multiwindow\i0\fs20\f0  or \i\fs18\f2 -fullscreen\i0\fs20\f0  the window will come up normally.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_cross_45_as_45_pointer}{\*\bkmkend ID_cross_45_as_45_pointer}\b 8.12. \b0 Why is the cross the default cursor in multiwindow mode?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 To workaround this add the command \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\f2 run xsetroot -cursor_name left_ptr -fg white -bg black\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \fs20\f0  to \fs18\f2 startxwin.bat\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_xterm_45_not_45_resizing}{\*\bkmkend ID_xterm_45_not_45_resizing}\b\fs20\f0 8.13. \b0 How can I adjust the linewidth in bash after resizing XTerm?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Try starting \fs18\f2 resize\fs20\f0 .\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_numlock_45_modifier}{\*\bkmkend ID_numlock_45_modifier}\b 8.14. \b0 Why do some menus not work if Num-Lock is on?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 The problem are programs which treat Num-Lock as modifier similar to Control. The programs expect a plain click but received some strange Num-Lock-Click combination and can't associate this with the action "open menu".\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li960\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_errors}{\*\bkmkend ID_errors}\b 9. Error and Warning Messages\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_owner_45_tmp_45__46_X11_45_unix}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_owner_45_tmp_45__46_X11_45_unix}9.1. \b0 _XSERVTransmkdir: Owner of /tmp/.X11-unix should be set to root\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 _XSERVTransmkdir: ERROR: euid != 0,directory /tmp/.X11-unix will not be created\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1024 This warning message can be ignored; it does not cause any known problems.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_error_45_security_45_policy}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_error_45_security_45_policy}\b 9.2. \b0 error opening security policy file /usr/X11R6/lib/X11/xserver/SecurityPolicy\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 This error is harmless.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_duplicate_45_invocation}{\*\bkmkend ID_duplicate_45_invocation}\b 9.3. \b0 Duplicate invocation on display number: 0. Exiting.\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Most likely you have started \fs18\f2 XWin.exe\fs20\f0  twice with \fs18\f2 startxwin.bat \fs20\f0 or \fs18\f2 startx\fs20\f0  or a similar script.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 if you start multiple instances of \fs18\f2 XWin.exe\fs20\f0  you have to start to number them\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl234 \fs18\f2 XWin.exe -query foo\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
XWin.exe :1 -query bar\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
XWin.exe :2 -query blubb\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \fs20\f0 Specifying no number is the same as using \i\fs18\f2 :0\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \i0\fs20\f0 If you want another terminal window (which in fact is just a convenient side effect of running \fs18\f2 startxwin.bat\fs20\f0 ) you should do this by starting \fs18\f2 xterm\fs20\f0  from the cygwin shell or from the startmenu entries.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_error_45_font_45_eof}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_error_45_font_45_eof}\b\lang1024 9.4. \b0 Fatal server error: could not open default font 'fixed'\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 This error occurs for one of three reasons:\hyphpar0\par\pard\li1800\sl260\fi-360 \tqr\tx1750\tx1800\tab 1.\tab You do not have a font package which provides the default font ('fixed') installed. This is rarely the problem; but in the event that it is the problem, just rerun Cygwin's \b setup.exe\b0 , select the font-misc-misc package and install it.\hyphpar0\par\pard\li1800\sl260\fi-360 \tqr\tx1750\tx1800\tab 2.\tab The mount point for \fs18\f2 /usr/share/fonts/\fs20\f0  was either invalid (does not point to a valid folder on your system) or is a text-mode mount. You can confirm that this is the problem by running \b mount\b0  from a Cygwin shell and checking the disk path returned for the \fs18\f2 /usr/share/fonts/\fs20\f0  mount point.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li2200\sl234 \b\fs18\f1 Note: \b0 You cannot reliably fix this problem by deleting your Cygwin installation and reinstalling it. The mount points that Cygwin was using will be left in your system settings and the invalid mount point for \fs16\f2 /usr/share/fonts/\fs18\f1  will be used again when you perform the reinstallation. You SHOULD follow the instructions below to fix the problem.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1800\sl260 \fs20\lang1033\f0 To fix the problem, perform the following steps:\hyphpar0\par\pard\li2160\sl260\fi-360 \tqr\tx2110\tx2160\tab \lang1024 a.\tab Open a Cygwin shell and run \b umount /usr/share/fonts/\b0 .\hyphpar0\par\pard\li2160\sl260\fi-360 \tqr\tx2110\tx2160\tab b.\tab Close the Cygwin shell.\hyphpar0\par\pard\li2160\sl260\fi-360 \tqr\tx2110\tx2160\tab c.\tab Run Cygwin's \b setup.exe\b0 .\hyphpar0\par\pard\li2160\sl260\fi-360 \tqr\tx2110\tx2160\tab d.\tab For each of the font packages, if they are marked Keep, then select Reinstall, otherwise leave them as they are:\hyphpar0\par\pard\li2160\sl260\fi-360 \tqr\tx2110\tx2160\tab e.\tab Allow Cygwin's \b setup.exe\b0  to download and reinstall the fonts packages. The key to fixing this problem is that the files were previously untarred into an invalid location; removing the mount point for the fonts directory should result in the files being untarred to a valid location.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1800\sl260\fi-360 \tqr\tx1750\tx1800\tab 3.\tab You chose "DOS/text" as the "Default Text File type" during Cygwin setup, ignoring the advice that the Default Text File Type should be left on Unix/binary unless you have a very good reason to switch it to DOS/text.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1800\sl260 \lang1033 Open a Cygwin shell and run.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1800\sl234 \fs18\lang1024\f2 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
umount /usr/share/fonts/\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
mount -f -s -b "C:/cygwin/usr/share/fonts" "/usr/share/fonts"\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1800\sl260 \fs20\lang1033\f0 Reinstall your fonts\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_removing_45_font_45_path_45_element}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_removing_45_font_45_path_45_element}\b\lang1024 9.5. \b0 Could not init font path element /usr/share/fonts/\i\fs18\f2 *\i0\fs20\f0 /, removing from list!\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 These warnings are generally harmless since they indicate that default search paths for fonts do not actually contain fonts; this is only a problem if the \fs18\f2 misc\fs20\f0  path does not contain fonts and/or all of the paths do not contain fonts.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 If you are getting these message and the X Server is also failing to start, then see {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_error_45_font_45_eof}{\fldrslt Q: 9.4.}} for information on how to fix your fonts.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_procedure_45_entry_45_point_45_missing}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_procedure_45_entry_45_point_45_missing}\b\lang1024 9.6. \b0 The procedure entry point _check_for_executable could not be located\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Programs that you are attempting to use were compiled against a newer version of Cygwin than is currently on your system. Run Cygwin's setup program to update your installation to the latest version.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_cygX11_45_6_46_dll_45_missing}{\*\bkmkend ID_cygX11_45_6_46_dll_45_missing}\b 9.7. \b0 cygX11-6.dll not found after installation or upgrade\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260  Obsolete question \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_status_45_access_45_violation}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_status_45_access_45_violation}\b 9.8. \b0 Exception: STATUS_ACCESS_VIOLATION\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 \fs18\f2 cygwin1.dll\fs20\f0  uses a shared memory section amongst all loaded copies of \fs18\f2 cygwin1.dll\fs20\f0 ; unfortunately, the layout and usage of the shared memory section changes between versions of \fs18\f2 cygwin1.dll\fs20\f0 . Loading two different versions of \fs18\f2 cygwin1.dll\fs20\f0  will cause the shared memory section to become corrupted, which almost always results in an Exception: STATUS_ACCESS_VIOLATION. You must search your filesystem(s) and remove all copies of \fs18\f2 cygwin1.dll\fs20\f0  except the copy in \fs18\f2 /bin\fs20\f0 . You must remove the different versions of \fs18\f2 cygwin1.dll\fs20\f0  even if they are not in your path, as programs that depend on \fs18\f2 cygwin1.dll\fs20\f0  attempt to load the file from the local directory before searching other paths; thus, it is rather easy, and common, for multiple versions of \fs18\f2 cygwin1.dll\fs20\f0  to become loaded at the same time if they exist on a particular system.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_error_45_max_45_clients}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_error_45_max_45_clients}\b 9.9. \b0 Xlib: connection to "\i\fs18\f2 local_host_name_or_ip_address\i0\fs20\f0 :0.0" refused by server Xlib: Maximum number of clients reached\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Cygwin/X queries getdtablesize () for the maximum number of client connections allowed; by default Cygwin returns 32 from getdtablesize (). Cygwin/X Server Test Series (http://x.cygwin.com/devel/server/) release Test44 (http://x.cygwin.com/devel/server/changelog.html), released on 2001-08-15, changes the maximum number of clients from 32 to 1024 by passing the square of getdtablesize () to setdtablesize ().\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_xio_45_fatal_45_io_45_error_45_104}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_xio_45_fatal_45_io_45_error_45_104}\b 9.10. \b0 XIO: fatal IO error 104 (Connection reset by peer) on X server "127.0.0.1:0.0"\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 See {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_error_45_max_45_clients}{\fldrslt Q: 9.9.}}\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_cannot_45_open_45_display}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_cannot_45_open_45_display}\b 9.11. \b0 Cannot Open Display: 127.0.0.1:0.0\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Certain classes of software, such as that used for {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_gloss_45_vpn}{\fldrslt \i Virtual Private Networking}} and {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_gloss_45_firewall}{\fldrslt \i fire-walling}} may cause the IP address 127.0.0.1, or other local adapter addresses, to be redirected, to become inoperable in some way, or to be operated in a manner that violates the defined operation of IP address.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 As a potential remedy, try removing all instances of such software; this may not always fix the problem though, as some software may leave artifacts even after uninstallation is completed. The only way to be sure that you have not found a Cygwin/X bug is to install Windows on a freshly formatted hard drive, followed by Cygwin and Cygwin/X, and finally add your other software one application at a time until Cygwin/X stops working.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 Some products that have been reported to cause problems: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1840\sl234 \b\fs18\f1 Note: \b0 These products may not cause problems in all configurations. However, the Cygwin/X project has neither the time, ability, nor resources to help you correctly configure your third-party software.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \fs20\f0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\li1640\sl260\fi-200 \tx1640 \fs16 \'95\tab \fs20 Aventail Connect\hyphpar0\par\pard\li1640\sl260\fi-200 \tx1640 \fs16 \'95\tab \fs20 Zonealarm PC Firewall from Zonelab\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_error_45_env_45_space}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_error_45_env_45_space}\b\lang1024 9.12. \b0 Out of environment space\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Increase your Windows environment space by following the instructions provided by Microsoft (http://support.microsoft.com/support/kb/articles/Q230/2/05.ASP).\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_too_45_many_45_parameters}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_too_45_many_45_parameters}\b 9.13. \b0 Too many parameters\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 See {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_error_45_env_45_space}{\fldrslt Q: 9.12.}}\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_xcb_45_lock_45_assertion}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_xcb_45_lock_45_assertion}\b 9.14. \b0 "xcb_xlib_lock: Assertion '!c->xlib.lock' failed." or "xcb_xlib_unlock: Assertion 'c->xlib.lock' failed." \keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260  Both of these represent bugs in a caller of libX11, and \i not\i0  in libX11 or libxcb. The first assertion means that a caller attempted to lock the display while already locked. The second assertion means that a caller attempted to unlock the display without having it locked. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 If you encounter such bugs, please report a bug against the offending software (which is \i not\i0  libX11 or libxcb)\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 This error can be worked around by using \b export LIBXCB_ALLOW_SLOPPY_LOCK=1\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li960\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_porting}{\*\bkmkend ID_porting}\lang1024 10. Porting Software\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_ported_45_software_45_list}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_ported_45_software_45_list}10.1. \b0 Is there a list of software that has been ported to Cygwin/X?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Yes, see the Cygwin/X - Ported Software (http://x.cygwin.com/ported-software.html) page.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_how_45_to_45_port}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_how_45_to_45_port}\b 10.2. \b0 How do I start porting software to Cygwin/X?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Cygwin/X provides a software interface that is very similar to the software interface provided by GNU/Linux and other UNIX systems. Most software packages will compile on Cygwin/X without any changes at all. To begin with, try to compile a given software package following that package's compilation instructions for GNU/Linux.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_common_45_porting_45_problems}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_common_45_porting_45_problems}\b 10.3. \b0 Are there common problems encountered when porting software to Cygwin/X?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 One common problem encountered when porting software to Cygwin/X is due to Cygwin's inability to distinguish between files with the same name but different capitalization (e.g. XvMC.h and xvmc.h), which is due to a Windows' limitation.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 \b Example 1. Include Problems\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \b0\lang1033 This example is based off an error that actually occurred in the source code tree in \fs18\f2 xc/programs/Xserver/Xext/xvmc.c\fs20\f0 . \fs18\f2 xvmc.c\fs20\f0  included \fs18\f2 XvMC.h\fs20\f0 , as shown below:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl234 \fs18\lang1024\f2 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
#include "XvMC.h"\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \fs20\lang1033\f0 The intention was to include the file \fs18\f2 xc/include/extensions/XvMC.h\fs20\f0 . Unfortunately, there was a file named \fs18\f2 xc/programs/Xserver/Xext/xvmc.h\fs20\f0  that ended up getting included instead of the desired file, because the precompiler searched the local directory, \fs18\f2 xc/programs/Xserver/Xext/\fs20\f0 , before searching the rest of the include path. Cygwin can't distinguish between \fs18\f2 XvMC.h\fs20\f0  and \fs18\f2 xvmc.h\fs20\f0 , so \fs18\f2 xvmc.h\fs20\f0  ended up being included in \fs18\f2 xvmc.c\fs20\f0 . The build process on Cygwin broke because the contents of \fs18\f2 XvMC.h\fs20\f0  were entirely different than the contents of \fs18\f2 xvmc.h\fs20\f0 .\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 The solution was to change the include to specifically reference the desired header:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl234 \fs18\lang1024\f2 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
#include "../../../include/extensions/XvMC.h"\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li960\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_contributing}{\*\bkmkend ID_contributing}\b\fs20\f0 11. Contributing\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_instructions_45_for_45_contributing}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_instructions_45_for_45_contributing}11.1. \b0 Are there step-by-step instructions for contributing to Cygwin/X?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Yes. The Cygwin/X Contributor's Guide (http://x.cygwin.com/docs/cg/cygwin-x-cg.html) has step-by-step instructions for obtaining the source, building the source, building debug versions of the source, and even cross-compiling under Linux.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_editors}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_editors}\b 11.2. \b0 Are there editors for Windows that understand and preserve UNIX end of line characters?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Yes. Emacs and XEmacs are available for Windows; they both understand and preserve UNIX end of line characters.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_contrib_45_diff}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_contrib_45_diff}\b 11.3. \b0 How should I generate patches for Cygwin/X?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Only submit patches that have UNIX end of line characters. See {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_editors}{\fldrslt Q: 11.2.}} for information on editors for Windows that are aware of UNIX end of line characters.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_where_45_to_45_submit_45_patches}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_where_45_to_45_submit_45_patches}\b 11.4. \b0 Where do I submit patches for Cygwin/X?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Submit patches for Cygwin/X to the cygwin-xfree@cygwin.com mailing list.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 See {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_contrib_45_diff}{\fldrslt Q: 11.3.}} for more information on generating patches.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_why_45_no_45_autoconf}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_why_45_no_45_autoconf}\b\lang1024 11.5. \b0 Why doesn't the X Window System use GNU's \b autoconf\b0 ?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 It does! Thanks to the excellent efforts of the X.Org community, the X Window System has been autotoolized since X.Org R7.0. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 Anyone who despaired of touching the monolithic tree will find things much easier now with modular packages.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_which_45_compilers_45_supported}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_which_45_compilers_45_supported}\b\lang1024 11.6. \b0 What compiler does Cygwin/X use, and which compilers are supported?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Cygwin/X uses the gcc compiler from the Free Software Foundation. Cygwin/X source code is mostly ANSI C compliant, but we cannot guarantee that Cygwin/X will compile with any other compiler, nor can we afford the time to support compilers other than gcc.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 See the GCC Home Page (http://gcc.gnu.org) for more information on gcc.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_cross_45_compiling}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_cross_45_compiling}\b\lang1024 11.7. \b0 Is cross-compiling from a non-Cygwin platform supported?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Cross-compiling from a non-Cygwin platform is described in the Cygwin/X Contributor's Guide (http://x.cygwin.com/docs/cg/cygwin-x-cg.html)\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_help_45_installing_45_docbook}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_help_45_installing_45_docbook}\b 11.8. \b0 Where can I get help for installing DocBook on Cygwin?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 See SGML for Windows NT: Setting up a free SGML editing and publishing system on Windows NT/Cygwin (http://web.archive.org/web/20050320030737/http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/hoenicka_markus/cygbook1.html) by Markus Hoenicka.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li960\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_license_45_ptc}{\*\bkmkend ID_license_45_ptc}\b 12. Licenses, Patents, Trademarks, and Copyrights\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_what_45_licenses_45_apply}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_what_45_licenses_45_apply}12.1. \b0 What licenses apply to Cygwin/X source code?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Cygwin/X proper isn't covered by a single license, as Cygwin/X is made up of two parts that are covered by distinct licenses: Cygwin and the X Window System.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 See {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_license_45_x_45_window_45_system}{\fldrslt Q: 12.2.}} and {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_license_45_cygwin}{\fldrslt Q: 12.3.}} for more information regarding the licenses that apply to Cygwin/X.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_license_45_x_45_window_45_system}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_license_45_x_45_window_45_system}\b\lang1024 12.2. \b0 What licenses apply to the X Window System source code?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 X Window System source code is generally licensed under an X11 style license (http://www.x.org/terms.htm), which is certified by the Free Software Foundation (http://www.fsf.org/philosophy/license-list.html#GPLCompatibleLicenses) as compatible with the GNU GPL.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_license_45_cygwin}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_license_45_cygwin}\b 12.3. \b0 What license applies to Cygwin source code?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Cygwin source code is licensed under a modified version of the GNU GPL. Cygwin's license modification specifically allows third-party software under an open source license to be linked with Cygwin without requiring that the source code for the third-party software be distributed under the terms of the GNU GPL. Cygwin's developers went to great trouble to obtain this modification and should be thanked for doing so, as without it the modification, Cygwin/X linking to Cygwin would be the subject of endless discussion.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_copyright_45_cygwin_45_x}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_copyright_45_cygwin_45_x}\b 12.4. \b0 Who holds the copyright on the Cygwin/X source code?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Cygwin/X proper doesn't have a single copyright holder, as Cygwin/X is made up of two parts, namely Cygwin and the X Window System; each part follows a different scheme in regards to who will hold the copyright on source code.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb100\li1440\sl260 \lang1033 See {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_copyright_45_x_45_window_45_system}{\fldrslt Q: 12.5.}} and {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_q_45_copyright_45_cygwin}{\fldrslt Q: 12.6.}} for more information regarding who holds the copyright on Cygwin/X source code.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_copyright_45_x_45_window_45_system}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_copyright_45_x_45_window_45_system}\b\lang1024 12.5. \b0 Who holds the copyright on the X Window System source code?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Each source code file in the X Window System typically has its own license and copyright statement. Therefore, there is not a general rule for determining who holds the copyright on a particular X Window System source file, as each author is free to assign the copyright to someone else, to some group, or to keep the copyright themselves. You must inspect the source code file in question to determine who holds the copyright for that file.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_copyright_45_cygwin}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_copyright_45_cygwin}\b 12.6. \b0 Who holds the copyright on the Cygwin source code?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 RedHat (http://redhat.com/) owns the copyright on the Cygwin source code. RedHat requires that copyright be assigned to RedHat for non-trivial changes to Cygwin. You must fill out a copyright transfer form if you are going to contribute substantial changes to Cygwin.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_motif_45_license}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_motif_45_license}\b 12.7. \b0 What license applies to Motif?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 Motif is a closed source product produced by The Open Group (http://www.opengroup.org/). However, The Open Group released Open Motif (http://www.opengroup.org/openmotif/) on 2000-05-15 under a public license, The Open Group Public License (http://www.opengroup.org/openmotif/license), that allows Open Motif to be distributed with and used on Open Source platforms. As of 2001-07-10, Cygwin/X does not qualify as a platform that Open Motif can be distributed with and used on. However, the Open Motif FAQ (http://www.opengroup.org/openmotif/faq.html) states, "[...] we hope to be able to make a distribution under a license complying with the Open Source guidelines sometime in the future. For now this is as close as to Open Source as we could get."\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb200\li1440\sl260 {\*\bkmkstart ID_q_45_trademark_45_xwin}{\*\bkmkend ID_q_45_trademark_45_xwin}\b 12.8. \b0 Isn't \'93XWin\'94 trademarked by StarNet Communications?\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb50\li1440\sl260 No. A quick search at the United States Patent and Trademark Office (http://www.uspto.gov/) for \'93XWin\'94 turns up one dead record and one live record. The live record is for a logo belonging to a rock crusher manufacturer based out of Belgium. Neither trademark affects Cygwin/X, as the dead record is no longer enforceable, while the live record is in an unrelated and distinct industry; there cannot be confusion between rock crushers and computer programs.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb216\s3\sl374 {\*\bkmkstart ID_biblio}{\*\bkmkend ID_biblio}\b\fs28\f1 Bibliography\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s2\sl449 \fs34 Books\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li1440\sl260\fi-480 \b0\fs20\f0 [ScheiflerGettys92]\~Robert W. Scheifler, James Gettys, Jim Flowers, and David Rosenthal, 1992, 1-55558-088-